message: Focus on cooking raw ingredients first. Proteins (fish, beef, bacon, eggs, beans) and vegetables (potato, tomato, pepper, broccoli, green beans, cucumber) increase to 20 value when cooked with the 'stove'. Grains (rice, wheat) need 'water' first to become 'soaked', then the 'stove' to be 'cooked soaked' and gain value. 'Tortilla' can be 'cooked' but its value remains 0 until combined. The highest value (100) items are typically a combination of **one cooked protein, one cooked grain, and one cooked vegetable**. Adding a fourth cooked item or combining raw vegetables into an already complex cooked dish often leads to 'overcomplicated' items with 0 or negative value. Stick to the 3-component strategy for max value!

message: Always use the stove to cook raw proteins and vegetables first, as this increases their base value. Combining 2-3 cooked items (e.g., protein + vegetable + grain) generally increases value. Be very careful adding a fourth cooked ingredient to an already complex item, as this often results in an 'overcomplicated' item with drastically reduced or negative value. For grains like rice, using water first then the stove seems to work better than just the stove. The maximum value is 100, and trying to exceed a good score like 80 or 100 can lead to an 'overcomplicated' item, so submit if you hit a high score and don't have a clear next step.
